

| *Abstract* In Sophocles’ *Oedipus Rex*, light is an ambiguous metaphor that undergirds the irony of the play.  Oedipus invokes the metaphor of light and inadvertently lies to himself and his subjects because of the metaphor’s ambiguity. The symbol of light, its unperceived ambiguity has been reflected throughout the ages. This article illustrates the ambiguity of  the metaphor of  light in Sophocles’ *Oedipus Rex*, light’s effect on Oedipus and the play’s plot, with comments from the 17th central empirical philosopher John Locke and others. |
| :---- |

[Locke](#locke)

Sunlight is a universal metaphor in human literature and life.

| But the light that we see every day, that illuminates darkness, that reveals truth, can also sometimes lie. In *Oedipus Tyrranous* the metaphor of light is a given. A promise of fulfilling and resolving. Sophocles’ audience has foreknowledge of the play, plot, characters, and catastrophe. Modern readers and audiences also already know Oedipus. Everyone knows Oedipus’ story except Oedipus himself. | ![][image1] |
| :---- | :---- |

The audience-anticipated irony is built into the light metaphor, semantically and syntactally.

	… authos auto ego phano.  
	I will bring all to the light.  
			– Lattimore

*Phanein* is a classical Greek root verb meaning *to research, to discover, to bring to light*.

Apollo himself is more than just basic light. He is the god of medicine and curing, of art, of of prophecy, of ambiguity, of contradiction. His light is shadowed by doubt and poetical ambiguous equivocation. He is the bright ????? wolf.
